The month of January is dedicated to Janus.
.
Janus is among the most ancient and significant deities of the Roman pantheon. 
.
Janus has two faces, indicating his power to see from all directions and perspectives. He sees the past and future simultaneously. Sometimes they’re depicted as one old and one young. 
.
The Roman Temple of Janus had double doors, known as the Gates of War. The temple was a visible symbol of peace or war. When there was peace throughout Rome, the doors of his temple were shut. This was a rare occurrence.
.
In 153 BCE, the Romans changed their calendar, moving the New Year from the spring equinox to 1 January, the feast day of Janus, Spirit of Beginnings. 
(The Romans switched to Jan 1st way before it was adopted as part of the Gregorian Calendar) 

With one face, Janus looks back on the old year; with the other he looks forward to the new. Roman New Year’s rituals incorporating the feast of Janus lasted for six days of joyous, raucous celebrating. Festivities included drinking, feasting, and decorating homes and buildings with holly, mistletoe, and lights.

.
You can visit his sacred site, The Janiculum Hill in Western Rome, center of his veneration. 
.
Tonight’s party, ringing in the New Year, is the worlds celebration of the this two-faced spirit. 

Janus not only brings us our months name, our New Year’s Eve tradition, but also the phrase “two-faced”.

Four years ago I printed out this image as our family’s business card and I set out to become a travel content creator. This little picture was handed out to destinations at conventions and landed us some pretty special opportunities. 
.
I’d been watching other accounts take off with travel collaborations and really desired to make it work for our little family. And God opened doors. For several years, pitches were sent and though many were rejected, each opportunity that opened up to us was a gift. Jaw on the floor, pinch-me-wake-me-up moments that I still can’t get over being offered, let alone experience with my most loved people. 
.
I started this account earlier this year to slowly build up a following of friends, genuine connections; people who truly want to be here. Forgoing the other account ( @wanderingdarlings ) was always the goal, despite the years having labored to make it what it was. It will always be a special place to tap on and see our past travels to fancy hotels, but the living in that space is over for us now and set to private. Our life looks differently, we have different goals for online connections and we hope to foster that over here with you. 
.
Laying the biggest dream in my heart, to continue traveling in this capacity, completely in God’s hands is humbling, to start all over and trust that if it’s meant to be, He will open doors as He did before. Sometimes it’s just time to close a chapter of your life and start again. 
.
I’m excited to go where He leads and I’m thankful to have you all here with us in this space and hope to meet you out in the real spaces, real soon. 
.
Now the only question is, what picture do I choose if I were to make new business cards? 🤔🤓

We’ve been keeping a secret. 
.
In an era where everyone shares everything down to the food they ordered for lunch, we’ve felt such a gift to keep this all to ourselves for so long. 
.
We couldn’t be more grateful for this opportunity to grow our family. The biggest blessings in life, and oh, to have five 🤍

Don’t be mad 😬 

There was one, teeny, tiny, other part to the secret. 

Surprise 👶🏼🎉

Keeping our pregnancy and birth offline was really so special. I remember as a little girl, reading a book on Shirley Temple where she was quoted as saying her adult life was lonely because as a child she had mistaken attention for adoration. Throughout this pregnancy I would reflect on that sentiment; one that as a culture we’ve all grown accustomed to a certain level of attention online and sometimes that can be mistaken for adoration; or the lack of attention equating to a lack of adoration. 
.
Having a public account for years has allowed me to feel that sentiment to a degree. Where you think you’ve got just the right picture or the right news to share just to be met with a lack luster response online from your friends and followers. 
.
But so much plays in to that absence of a response, but our emotional connection to desiring a specific reaction can often times turn those great pictures or that exciting news into less than they really are because we are conditioned to look for responses to what we shared online. 
.
To keep one of the most personal, sacred moments of our life to ourselves allowed us to just revel in it. An untainted gestation of hope, dreams, and unbearably large love for the tiniest life. 
.
Here’s a glimpse in to our first month as a family of seven. We never left home, stayed in pajamas, and took turns cuddling the son that was always meant to be. There’s so much love for this little boy 💙 
.

It was early morning when we met our fifth child. 
My labor was under an hour from the first pain till my eyes saw him for the very first time. 
He entered the world, safely at home, in our bed, with his four siblings standing behind my shoulders waiting for him. 
I’ll never forget the extraordinary experience of looking at my four other children while I birthed him. 
His oldest sister was the first to see his gender and announce it to our family. His brothers cut his cord. My recovery was instantly in bed with all (5!) of my children in bed with me while we cried of happiness together. 
.
His name is Arlo, which is derived from a Celtic (my heritage) word Aherlow, meaning “between two highlands” or between two hills. 
.
Between our fourth and fifth there’s a five year age gap. One that will always remind me of my season of first depression and then fear of the unknown. It wasn’t until I surrendered my fears to the Lord that I was immediately pregnant, just to witness that baby leave this earth before it ever left my body. 
And then, Arlo, the beautiful little boy that will remind me of that place between two hills; the place where you find God; all you have to do is look up. 
.
I respect that not all desire a home birth nor is a home birth an option for every mother. My experience was redemptive in every way and I’m forever grateful our story was as quick and intimate as it was. However you bring your child in to the world is worthy to be celebrated. It’s no small feat, motherhood.

Two, now big sisters, and I, find ourselves looking for ways to spend time together with a baby in my arms.
.
We have found story time makes us all happy, together. Listening on audio is enjoyable for us all and you can be hands occupied while doing so ☺️ Here is what we’ve been enjoying; 
The following titles are all for the younger child and are included with an @audible account.

When We Were Six, A. A. Milne 
Narrated by, Peter Dennis 

When We Were Very Young, A. A. Milne 
Narrated by, Peter Dennis 

Tales of Beatrix Potter 
Narrated by, Nadia May

Just So Stories, Rudyard Kipling 
Narrated by, Johanna Ward

The Ugly Duckling, Hans Christian Andersen 
Narrated by, Stephan mangan 

Stone Soup, European Folk Story 
Narrated by, Heather Forest 
.

Do you struggle with capturing your children when out on an adventure? Here’s what you do: 

• Look around for the area you want in the frame, the corner in a room, a flower field, a pretty city street, down by the sea, etc., 

• Then tell your children you want them to stand within that framed area and encourage them to MOVE!!! Skipping, twirling, walking, touching the flowers, jumping on beds; these are the moments your kids thrive in! 

The ones where they feel most like children! 

So, don’t worry about stressing out that your kids don’t want to stand still or smile genuinely at the camera. 

Let them be them and you work to find a pretty space for the photograph. 

The two combined equal family keepsakes. Pretty backgrounds + happy children.

Last year we put our children in organized sports, for basically the first time. The boys instantly loved spring baseball, the two middles played soccer and then dance for the girls. It was such a crazy season, we had an activity 6 days of the week and it was not for us 😅 round of applause for those of you who thrive on busy schedules 👏🏼 

We took the summer off of activities to travel and God laughed and said, no. So, we enjoyed a quiet summer at home. With the exceptions of two jaunts down to Florida, where the sun seems to haaaate me ☀️ but round of applause to those of you who can spend time in Florida without going to bed with raw potato on your skin 👏🏼 yeah, I said raw potato. 

Our fall trips got canceled for various reasons and then we got too close to baby’s due date (which is a fun story because we didn’t actually know when that was because turns out that when your first ultrasound is in your third trimester it’s too hard to say how far along you are because baby might be measuring correctly, but also likely baby is measuring smaller or bigger). So, again we stayed home which allowed baseball/soccer fun to take place again - we withheld the girls from dance for the season to maintain our sanity. 

We made the call to take newborn time as a family with nothing on the schedule and it’s been the best - but now we are looking at activities again because the kids love them so much. 

So, tell me - what do your kids do for extracurricular? If you have a large family, do they alternate or all do it at the same time? Is there a limit to how many activities you allow each kid to do? 

And final Round of applause for those of you who actually read through this entire thing 👏🏼And I know it seems pointless to talk about. But I need to hear what other families choose because others’ experiences help.

After I had Clementine I plummeted in to a two year long battle of depression. Looking back, aside from hormonal changes post birth, it is easy to see how I opened the door for this. 

I used those early weeks of late night feedings to let my mind wander down all of the things I could do with a year off of work and being at home with my kids - a chance to pursue dreams, I thought! 

So I enrolled in college, online, to finish my degree. I took an anatomy class and a classic literature class. I also opened up a two small businesses, an online woman’s boutique with an acquaintance, and a toy shop, with my family. In addition to pursuing content creation. 

Clementine and I ran in to some health bumps with breastfeeding and we needed to feed her what I pumped - so, with the heartache of not nursing her, I sat hooked up to a machine and read things like the Canterbury Tales, memorizing definitions of strange terms like Foramina and the Circle of Willis. Pitching emails, running marketing for two shops, photography, and doing business finances on top of schooling the boys at home. 

All while hearing, “you’re amazing! How do you do so much?” In truth, there wasn’t a time that my brain was not running a mile a minute, yet my body could barely move. I sat holding Clementine as much as I could, a much needed anchor to the chaos I’d invited in to my mind. 

I remember how it was possible to sit in utter darkness even though I had the light of my children dancing around me all day, like stars hanging on tightly to the blackness of sky. 

This time, when I sit and hold my precious baby, I will my mind to not think this time of slowness, sluggish mornings from a night barely slept, afternoon lulls that no caffeine pick-me-up can really quench; is not the time to add dreams to these days. 

Because these days are the dream. In and of themselves, better than broadening your mind, taking business ventures, being inspired artistically; all wonderful, but none that are worth more than this. 

So my mind; settle. And rest. With your baby in your arms, knowing you’re held by the Father’s arms. 
Don’t dream too much, let peace just be.

We didn’t find out the gender of our baby (never have for any of them and man, there’s no greater treat than hearing it for the first time after all of that work getting them here!) 
.
The girls were hopeful for boy and girl twins - even when they knew it was absolutely only one baby, they kept hoping (God is a God of miracles, they will tell you). The idea of them only getting one baby was not their favorite thing because they knew they’d only have either a brother or sister. 

We talked a lot about how the baby was chosen specifically for our our family and whoever it was going to be is who God chose and knows we need in our life. 

When our baby was still covered on my chest, and Delphine was able to look and announce to our family, I heard a sob behind me and I looked back over my shoulder where Clementine was in her father’s arms and said, “ oh are you disappointed?” My voice cracking and the camera cutting off so she could be loved on by her daddy. I was so sad for her in that one moment; I’ve been there before with a little boy who was sad Clementine herself wasn’t a baby brother. 

But I knew; this will last just a moment and then sure enough, as she came and tucked herself into my arm and gazed over at the miraculous little brother she was gifted, nothing but love could be seen. An instant love so powerful. 

Truly something beautiful to have witnessed two different five year olds meet a new baby and watch their countenance come to grips with loss of hope and refilled with love beyond measure. 
And five years after I watched Jude’s shoulders sink upon hearing “sister” I watched him spend the first few weeks crying tears of joy while he held the baby brother he always longed for. 
God knows exactly who we need and when we need them 💙 
And even if we don’t have a little sister to match with, we are going to find a way to match. ☺️

Have you ever heard of Georgia Tann? She was an American child trafficker who operated the Tennessee Children's Home Society. Georgia had a high profile father and lots of connections.
Tann used a variety of methods to procure children. Through pressure tactics, threats of legal action, and other ways, she would coerce birth parents, mostly poor single mothers, to turn the children over to her custody, often under false pretenses. 
Tann also arranged for the taking of children born to inmates at Tennessee mental institutions and those born to wards of the state through her connections. To meet demand, she resorted to kidnappings, often children from their very own front porches. 
Tann was documented taking children born to unwed mothers at birth, claiming that the newborns required medical care. When the mothers asked about the children, Tann or her accomplices would explain that the babies had died, when they had actually been placed in foster homes or adopted. It is estimated that she stole over 5,000 children in Tennessee. 
Records show the children from the home went to high profile clients, like two of Joan Crawford’s children, as well as supplying children to politicians across America. 
The governor of the time, applied to investigate Georgia and the home she ran on 9/11 1950 but she died 3 days before it went to court. 
Her story is absolutely appalling and heartbreaking. Several survivors of her abusives orphanage have written books on their experiences there and their pursuit for their biological families; most never reunited.

When in Hartford, we stopped by Mark Twains house. We learned a lot about the author and the family man, Samuel Clemens, while on the tour. But we still had a ton of questions after so we had to do some more research. 
He maintained that his primary pen name came from his years working on Mississippi riverboats, where two fathoms, a depth indicating water safe for the passage of boat, was a measure on the sounding line.
His house used to sit on a river that the government filled in, was finished in 1847 and home to him, his wife, and three daughters. My kids appreciated seeing the house, but I wish the tour also included the servants quarters as the Clemens had a staff of 12 at all times and I’m just as interested in how they lived, not just the rich people up front. 
.
We learned that Mr. Twain wrote all of his famous books in this house, was friends with President Grant and he’d come over to play pool with Twain. Twain was gifted a piano from someone and it came with 33 free lessons. His wife thought he talked too much and would work the word ‘blue into conversation to let him know to stop talking. Alexander Graham Bell asked Twain to help fund the world’s first telephone and Twain was too broke to help his friend out, but still was the first home in America to have a working telephone (also the first home in America to have a full working bathroom). 
.
Our own research showed he was very good friends with Nikola Tesla, was vice president of the anti-imperialist league and was given honorary entry into Yale’s secret society Scroll and Key. 
.
His house is said to be America’s Downton Abbey and although I wouldn’t say it’s as WOW as that house, it’s certainly worth a visit, but sadly no pictures of the interior are allowed so I can’t share with you his tremendous wallpaper collection!

The Great Sabbath; Shabbat HaGadol
Jesus' last Passover: After visiting his friend Lazarus and his sisters in Bethany, He went to Jerusalem just before the city became filled with pilgrims coming to celebrate the holiday. On the 10th of Nisan He entered the city, riding on a donkey to announce His Messiahship (this was the time the lamb was being selected for the Passover sacrifice). Examined for four days before His sacrifice (execution) for the sins of the world, He was found to be the true Lamb of God without spot or blemish.

The Holy City would have been a busy place, bustling with excitement and (due to Roman oppression) filled with Messianic expectation. The Law required (Ex. 12:1-6) that each family select a lamb (called korban Pesach) four days before the sacrifice was to be offered at the Temple. During this time the lamb would be examined to ensure that it was defect-free and therefore acceptable for sacrifice at the Temple.

I can see the signs of new things coming and I’m excited, but I also need to take a minute to cry over how in five years time my oldest can no longer hug on to me like this.

I wanted to make a reel, but pretty sure the length of this one leans more mini movie. 
Here’s little clips of some of our collected memories,  our home videos, I imagine we will play these for the children when they have children of their own, and we will all talk about the little blue houses and the big orange sunsets @gulfsideresorts .

Over the last few years, we’ve had the honor of being guests at some of the most remarkable resort destinations. As content creators, we focused on family luxury travel. 
We’ve seen some of the prettiest properties and slept in the comfiest beds, fancy room service, resort amenities, all catered to families. 

But here’s the truth; if you could only take one trip that I’ve been on, I’d tell you to take this one. @gulfsideresorts has the most charming property called Sarah’s Seaside, a handful of bungalows, ranging in capacity; a shared pool that leans more “backyard” than “resort”. A lush garden of landscaping that make you feel like you’ve stepped in to another world, as it’s a stark contrast from the world outside it. The walk to the beach; is private and short and you feel like you have the whole beach to yourselves. 
@gulfsideresorts feels like a vacation, but it also feels like a home. Like you’re personal guests, staying in a guest house. The staff are all wonderful and sincere. The guests are usually repeat guests because they love it so much. 
@gulfsideresorts is owned by the same couple who bought their first property 30 years ago (they own a few properties in Indian Rock Beach). 

They’ve made a charming little escape at Sarah’s Seaside, next to the sea, out of these little historic, blue houses.
We will always love you @gulfsideresorts

Do you ever look up the stories that make up the past of where your present is? 

It is said that Indian Rocks Beach got its name from a medicine man who used the local waters to heal his very ill chief, Chief Chic-a-Si. 

The healing water is said to have come from the natural sulfur springs, believed to have been located in Kolb Park. After the miraculous healing, the Indians returned to the site on a pilgrimage each year to fish and drink the water. Early settlers are said to have observed the Indians “going to the rocks” each year, giving the beach its name. 
-
In Tampa, there is one hill, and it’s not a natural hill. It was made by the Tocobaga Indians; the temple mound would have been a place where the Tocobaga prepared their deceased relatives for burial and where the Chief and their close kin would have lived. 
-
It is believed that in approximately 1528, Pánfilo de Narváez, a Spanish explorer, arrived in the Tampa Bay area. He and his men found the Tocobaga and brought disease and violence to the tribe's peaceful existence. As a result, the Tocobaga Indians became extinct within the next 100 years.

Happy Sabbath, friends. 
.

We’ve been preparing to make this home for someone else. Originally, we thought we had mere paint touchups to do and then could pass this home on to someone new. 
• But we found that one side of the house, the wood has rotted, so my husband spent two weeks putting new siding up on the house and painting. Then we took a wonderful getaway down to Florida and @gulfsideresorts 
• Just to come back to some rainy days that quickly showed us we had a leak in the roof and it needed repairing. When they came to inspect the area of the leak, we were informed we needed a new roof 😅 we’ve been working with insurance to see what they’ll cover and then having that work done. 
• Then our dishwasher broke (outside of the warranty window) and my husband had to learn yet another new skill to fix it. 
• Then the yard started smelling poopy, so we had the sceptic tank cleaned out and serviced - we ruled out we weren’t the cause for the smell, but we couldn’t get it to go away. Last night, my husband walked down to the creek in our backyard and noticed the water was sludge and smelly. He called the town, who sent the right people over, and we found out that a sewage line broke and is draining in to the natural waterway. 
•I’m sitting here with the windows open, poop scent wafting in and wondering why in the world this is the moment in time that God said, “move.” 

Do you know anybody who wants a poop creek? The roof will be brand new; so worth it.

We’ve always dreamt of taking a year off and traveling; our gap year. It’s been a decade of dreams and we thought this summer would be the perfect time to begin it. Sam is leaving his current job and we thought we’d travel abroad with the kids and have all kinds of amazing experiences; traveling slow, staying weeks at a time in one place. Learning the culture, meeting the people, and just soaking in what it’s like to do life elsewhere. We imagined traveling to different churches and collecting friendships all over the world. 
But Yah opened up an opportunity for Sam to start a new job and it’s an opportunity we don’t want to miss, so that gap year is delayed indefinitely. 

Before it wasn’t though, I asked Sam at the end of last year, “where is the first place you’d want to go?” With Iceland already as my suggestion in my head, I was ready to share it when suggested something else, he put some thought in to it and he said, “Iceland”. And so it was. 
 
We didn’t even have Iceland on our minds for this summer, but Yah. So, here we are. Exactly where we dreamt we’d go this summer to start a new chapter in life. And though this new chapter looks different than we had ever imagined, I’m really grateful that I’m learning to let go of what we wanted and be open to what Yah has planned for us instead. 

Loosening the grasp of my own desires and receiving His will over my own; one day at a time over here. 

And just really grateful He made lupine.

Not your typical summer destination, but it should be on the list. 

#greenlandpioneer #greenlandtravel #visitgreenland #greenlandic #travelwithkids

We try to learn everything we can about a place that we are. Here’s 5 of our favorite Iceland facts we learned. 

🐢 it’s illegal to own a lizard or turtle. There are no reptiles on Iceland. 

🐏 delicacies like raw puffin heart, the rest of the puffin, ram testicles, lamb’s loin, whale meat and shark meat are popular among locals. 

🧝 As many as 80 percent of the population of Icelanders still believe in the existence of elves. Even today some roads have been rerouted so as not to disturb rocks or other places said to be the homes of elves. 

🔫 Iceland has no standing army, but the Coast Guard maintains the Iceland Air Defense System and patrols coastal waters. The police force doesn’t carry any guns 

🍌 Iceland is nearly self sufficient and rely on very little of the outside world, they even grow their own bananas. 

Top travel tip is always take a taxi ride with a native behind the wheel and let them proudly tell you about the place they call home. We make a point of doing it at least once to hear from someone’s real perspective 🤍 i promise they’ll appreciate that you asked.

Back in February, I made some stories sharing that we wanted to bring my husband home from working on Saturdays. Over the last two years, we’ve come to the belief that the seventh day is to be kept Holy for Yahuah. The kids and I were able to make a day of rest, but my husband could not; despite his requests his employer would not honor him a swap in work days. 
That night, a girl who had read my stories, suggested a a job opportunity in aviation, not knowing my husbands exact resume or experience. We decided to look in to it and they had a job opening posted. The job, oddly enough, encompassed all of what my husband has done in his career, both in military and commercial aviation. The only thing was the job available was in Greece. Immediately, I thought it was exciting, with biblical history and Greek mythology both being of huge interest to me. And we really didn’t think the odds would be in his favor. 
He applied and then we left for TN. Our hearts were longing to call TN home, with friends there we’d love to be close to. But during our stay, we pulled over on the way to a friends house and the kids and I sat in a parking lot while Sam went into a hotel lobby to have his virtual interview. 
When there, we decided to look at model homes, where we had a nice long, likeminded conversation with the realtor and as she was seeing us out of the door (we told her nothing about Greece) she said, “God often has us move to the place we’d be the most uncomfortable in.” And Sam and I looked at each other, did Yah just use her to tell us TN might not be it? 
Weeks later, Sam found out he had been selected for the job and we just couldn’t believe how Yah had brought it to be. 
If I hadn’t said it in my stories, on an impulse one night. If that one girl hasn’t seen my stories, you know how few they show it to. If I hadn’t opened her message in time to see the job listing; it expired just a few days after we saw it and we had to scramble to update his resume. If his entire career hadn’t given him the ability to even apply. 
And so, here we are, because we sought to seek the sabbath and Yah found us a way. Because sometimes He moves us to where we are most uncomfortable.

Let’s talk SUNDAYS in Greece 🇬🇷 

Guys! As you can see here, a Sunday afternoon in Corinth - Greece closes shop! There’s barely anyone around! 

Small boutique shops are closed!

Grocery stores are closed!

Produce markets, fish markets, butcher shops; closed!

Pharmacies are closed! 

The MALL is closed!! 

Now, there are exceptions - usually in one residential area, there’s multiple pharmacies, so one will remain open on a Sunday and then they’ll rotate through the other Sundays taking their turn to be open for the area.

There is an outlet mall near Athens Airport that remains open on Sundays, as well as the IKEA. 

But when I say they close up on Sundays, I mean it! It’s so fascinating to us! 

I have even read that Greek law mandates that every Sunday throughout the year is designated as a public holiday!

So Americans, don’t take that Sunday shopping for granted! I know some of you feel the pangs on Sunday when you can’t get to Chick-fil-A 😬😉

As Saturday sabbath keepers, we don’t shop on Saturdays and would typically use Sunday as a day to pick up what we need, so this has been a very interesting thing to get used to. 

Though we keep a different sabbath day as they do here in Greece, I think it’s extremely respectful that they have set apart a day to not shop. 

* restaurants, for the most part, are still open on Sundays 😌

Did you know this about Greece? Are there other countries that close shopping on Sundays?

The Acropolis of Ancient Corinth, Akrokorinthos, is a magnificent castle that is built on a monolithic rock. It is one of the biggest castles in Europe and the largest one in Greece. 

The castle is originally from 6 BC  and here are some of my favorite stories that belong to these rocks. 

It was once a place to worship Aphrodite and 3,000 prostitutes lived within the walls - sailors would come (and I’m sure others) to do their thing with the ladies, who were said to have the ability to plead to Aphrodite on their behalf. 

On the mountain, within the castle walls, is a spring where it was said that the winged horse Pegasus struck the ground with its hoof and created the spring. 

It is also said that this spring exists because of the nymph, Peirene, who cried when her son was unintentionally killed by Artemis and cried herself this spring of tears. 

And lastly, the Apostle Paul is said to have preached here, there’s even a room where they say he taught in. 

Some would say some of those stories are just myths, but I’d say they’re all theology. What would you say?

The most romantic city (even with five kids in tow) is definitely; Nafplio! 

Cutest place in Greece, with soooo much color 💕 
It feels so charming, I’ve wanted to go back since before we even left. 

If you are planning a trip to Greece and will be staying in or around Athens, Nafplio is definitely worth the trip!

Everywhere we go there’s a story; This is Sparta 

Named for the daughter of a king named Eurotas. Local people say he was a river god, and his daughter a nymph. Others say that Sparta was a mere mortal girl and her father dug out the river, now called the Eurotas. 

Sparta was married to Lacedaemon, the son of Zeus. Because Eurotas had no sons, Lacedaemon became king over this area, naming the land after himself, and his thriving city, Sparta, after his wife. 

Our journey to Sparta was by way of Mt Taygetus. These mountains have a deep history, Plutarch said that Sparta had a ritual where they’d bring newborn babies to be judged by the elders and those thought unfit to be allowed to live were left at the foot of Mount Taygetos. It is also said that there are  beehive tombs within the mountains, where Sparta would hold captives, human remains have been found all throughout the mountains.

The art within the structures here in Barcelona and the Andalucian area of Spain is just incredible. Oh, to think about what lays in our past, hidden in the shadows of the term, “the dark ages”. 

All of this art, up to the highest point of the arched ceilings, certainly tells a story in a language that only those who were around to make it, understand.
